        description: "Vernon, gateway to Giverny and Claude Monet's gardens, is 45 minutes from Rouen via the A13.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A13 along the Seine valley towards Paris, exit Vernon.",
        introduction: "Vernon is a charming Seine valley town, world-famous as the gateway to Giverny, the village where Claude Monet lived from 1883 until his death in 1926 and painted his most celebrated masterpieces: the Water Lilies, the Japanese Bridge, the irises, the wisteria. The Claude Monet Foundation in Giverny (Monet's house, studios and gardens) is France's most visited Impressionist site, attracting over 700,000 visitors per year. The gardens, designed by Monet himself, are a living painting: the water garden with its lily pond and Japanese bridge (painted 250 times by Monet), and the Clos Normand with its brilliant flower beds changing with the seasons. The Impressionism Museum Giverny, nearby, hosts temporary exhibitions on Impressionism and Post-Impressionism. Vernon itself has discreet charm: the medieval old mill perched on a former Seine bridge (one of Normandy's most photographed images), the Notre-Dame Collegiate Church (11th-16th c.) and half-timbered houses of the old town. The Château des Tourelles, a medieval fortress facing the old mill, guards the former bridge.",
        itineraire: "Your driver takes the A13 from Rouen towards Paris. The motorway follows the Seine with fine views of the river's meanders and forested chalk cliffs. You pass Les Andelys, where Richard the Lionheart's Château Gaillard dominates the valley from its promontory. The Vernon exit is about 60 km from Rouen. Your driver can drop you directly at Giverny (4 km from Vernon), at the Claude Monet Foundation or the Impressionism Museum. A13 tolls amount to about €6 (included). Allow 45 minutes normally.",
        conseils: "The Claude Monet Foundation at Giverny (€11) is essential — arrive at opening (9:30 am) to enjoy the gardens before the crowds (very busy, especially May to July when the water lilies bloom). The water garden is at its finest from May to September. The Impressionism Museum Giverny (€8) presents high-quality temporary exhibitions. In Vernon, the old mill on the Seine is the most photographed spot: access via the riverside footpath. Château Gaillard at Les Andelys (en route, A13 exit) merits a 15-minute detour for its medieval ruins and Seine panorama. The Restaurant Baudy in Giverny is the former Impressionists' inn (Monet, Renoir, Cézanne dined there). The Monet Foundation is open April to November.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The TER Rouen — Vernon takes about 40 min (direct, ~€11, 5-6 trains/day). From Vernon station, a shuttle bus serves Giverny (4 km, €5, 10 min) during Monet Foundation opening hours. The TaxiNeo taxi at €80 — €95 is direct door-to-door to the Monet Foundation in 45 minutes, with no shuttle wait. For 3-4 passengers (€20-32/person), competitive with train + shuttle (€16-21/person) with much more comfort and flexibility.",
